From: wasm-nommu
Subject: libbb: compile out xfork() on wasm even when BB_MMU=1

The existing #if BB_MMU guard on xfork() was designed for uClibc NOMMU
systems.  wasm32 busybox builds that use allnoconfig (e.g. ash.nix) do
NOT set CONFIG_NOMMU=y (ash depends on !NOMMU in Kconfig), so BB_MMU=1
and xfork() is compiled — but wasm musl ships no fork() symbol (fork is
unimplementable on the clone-with-fn NOMMU model).

This patch (applies after 0004) extends xfork()'s guard to
`#if BB_MMU && !defined(__wasm__)` so the ash.nix allnoconfig build does
not reference the absent fork symbol. xfork() has no enabled caller on
the guest, so making the symbol ABSENT means any future caller fails
loudly at static-link time rather than linking a runtime abort stub.

(xvfork_parent_waits_and_exits() is compiled out for ALL wasm configs by
patch 0004's `#if !defined(__wasm__)` guard — no separate handling here.)

diff -ruN a/libbb/xfuncs_printf.c b/libbb/xfuncs_printf.c
--- a/libbb/xfuncs_printf.c	2026-06-21 19:14:08.942964416 -0400
+++ b/libbb/xfuncs_printf.c	2026-06-21 19:13:58.371809432 -0400
@@ -685,7 +685,8 @@
 	buf[4 + 2 + 2] = (buf[4 + 2 + 2] & 0x3f) | 0x80;
 }
 
-#if BB_MMU
+/* wasm32: no fork even with BB_MMU=1 (allnoconfig ash build). */
+#if BB_MMU && !defined(__wasm__)
 pid_t FAST_FUNC xfork(void)
 {
 	pid_t pid;
